Cold, adversarial QA verification of COD-123 against the ticket below and this slice's diff against the base branch. Treat the code on disk and the ticket as the only sources of truth; your job is to find what does NOT work. Run only the tests relevant to this slice (the new or changed test files for this ticket) using the project's test runner (in a multi-workspace repo, the affected workspace's own runner) — not the whole suite. No separate QA brief was written for this tiny slice: derive the concrete, checkable behaviors yourself from the ticket and the diff, then confirm each actually holds.  Distinguish defects in this slice's own code from pre-existing or out-of-scope issues. When finished, write a JSON verdict to exactly /tmp/verify-COD-123.json: {"pass": true|false, "summary": "one line", "failures": ["..."], "browser": "driven"|"skipped"|"not-applicable", "browser_notes": "what you exercised, or the concrete reason the browser could not be driven"}. Set pass=false if any relevant test fails or any behavior the ticket requires does not work; failures lists each concrete problem (empty when pass is true). Account for browser QA honestly: set "browser" to "driven" when you exercised this slice's UI in a real browser, "not-applicable" only for a backend-only slice with no UI surface, or "skipped" when a UI surface went undriven. This is an unattended run against a sanctioned, dedicated automation browser — never skip a UI surface out of concern for a user's session, and if the browser cannot connect, set "skipped" and report the concrete reason in "browser_notes" instead of silently omitting it. Do not commit, push, or open a PR.